* STEM toys are strongly marketed to boys. - CITATION: http://www.theiet.org/policy/media/press-releases/20161206.cfm

* In girls as young as 5 discussion of subjects traditionally seen as masculine (STEM and sports) cause girls to perform worse on STEM tests, regardless of actual ability - CITATION: http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1111/1467-9280.00371

* STEM teachers hold subconscious biases that boys are better at STEM subjects. - CITATION: http://www.ecu.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/unconscious-bias-and-higher-education.pdf

* Exposure to negative stereotypes about women's genetic predisposition to STEM cause girls to perform worse on STEM tests, regardless of actual ability. - CITATION: https://panet.andover.edu/bbcswebdav/institution/SCIE/SCIE/science%20490/exposure%20to%20scientific%20theories%20affects%20womens%20math%20performance.pdf

* Girls who think of themselves as feminine are more likely to think STEM subjects aren't for them, regardless of actual ability - CITATION: https://www.kcl.ac.uk/sspp/departments/education/research/aspires/ASPIRES-final-report-December-2013.pdf

* Math tests are actually a very inaccurate way to evaluate math skills, which causes girls' actual math abilities to be underestimated - CITATION: https://web.stanford.edu/~niederle/NV.JEP.pdf

* Female teachers struggling with their own internalized math anxiety (because of the pre-existing society issues) pass that on to their female students - CITATION: http://www.pnas.org/content/107/5/1860.full.pdf

* Studies suggest that the gender gap in math scores tends to disappear in cultures with better gender equality - CITATION: http://science.sciencemag.org/content/320/5880/1164.summary?ck=nck

That people still fail to understand how these, and countless other social factors at play, lead to low interest in STEM majors by the time these girls get to college that they don't know they are being willfully blind to the impact that society and culture has on all of us is so frustrating.
